feedback: It was kind of hard to figure out a pattern. The family with heads seemed to be more in family 2.

I tried to scan the examples fairly quickly and determine which family had mostly all three features and which had mostly single features. Two features seemed to be more closely distributed between the two families. When selecting families, I made mental notes to try to ensure I put at least one of each type of feature combination in each family, then distributed the primary feature set (1 or 3) into their respective families almost entirely.
I looked for certain combinations of figures as clues, and also the presence or lack there off certain features.

For the first it just seemed like it was family 1 if there was only 1 feature and family 2 if there was more than 1, but during the task I started second guessing the perception. For the second I just tried to go with my instinctive perceptions, though it did seem like no head made family 2 more likely.
I used patterns in the images to see which family they would more likely belong to depending on the features it did or did not have.

in the first test i thought i found some pattern but don't think in the end that i got it correct. In the second it appeared that until the man was made whole again it was one family or the other and then once it showed the whole man again it was the next family. not sure if that was correct or not.
Tried to see which patterns belonged more with each family. Probably unsuccessfully.
I just tried to remember which part or combination of parts belonged to which family although I felt that sometimes they seemed to belong in both.
In  the first it seemed that more single features were in family one and in the second experiment it seemed that more head with arms, arms or full feature were with family one
three dots and just legs were definitely 2, one dot on the right and all three body parts were definitely 1, the rest were pretty arbitrary
family 1 in the first one, seemed to usually have single circles. or ones that were separated. Family 1 in the second experiment, seemed to always have a 'head'.
I noticed in both that one family had a lot more of the only one figures.
I just tried to memorize which family the objects belonged to. I did not have any strategies. I did not notice any patterns.

I began with the family with all three elements and decided which family that belonged to, then looked for patterns with just one element, then used process of elimination and/or instinct for the rest.
in the first one - if there were 2 or more I selected 2. In the second one, I selected half 1 and half 2
I tried to pay attention to which families had arms, legs, etc.

I looked at which features appeared the most for each family. I noticed one feature (circle) would only usually show up under the "1" family in the first task, while figures showing 2 or 3 features/circles appeared more under the "2" family. In the 2nd task, I seemed to notice the "head (circle)" appeared the most under the "1" family.

This was very difficult to me.  Attempting to establish a pattern while only seeing a single image at a time was not easy at all, but I tried to note commonalities between groupings as well as I was able to.  I do not believe I did well at all on the second grouping.
